(100, 2, '2019-08-28 21:41:12', '2019-08-29 01:41:12', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It\'s late August and I\'m my pepper plants are finally starting to produce some fruit for the picking.  I\'ve been looking forward to this all summer!  I was feeling like something with a little sweet chilli heat so I decided to pick the first 3 peppers of the year and brew up some mango habanero sauce.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The sauce is pretty basic consisting of only 7 ingredients including vinegar which isn\'t in the picture.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":104} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8888/TheHotPickle/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/IMG_1887.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-104\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I took the seed out of the peppers and found it still had some big kick at then end.  I love the flavour of habanero so I wanted as much pepper in this as I could stand.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Peel your garlic, render down your garlic and toss them along with the peppers into a blender.  Add your vinegar, molasses and salt and blend until smooth.  I used my Vitamix this time however next time I think I\'ll just use the hand blender.  There\'s just not enough liquid to get the blender flowing, not to mention it\'s a much bigger pain to clean.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":105} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8888/TheHotPickle/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/IMG_1894.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-105\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The next step is to get a few tablespoons of water to boil in a small crock pot and mix in the sugar.  We\'re basically just making a small amount of simple syrup here and once the sugar is dissolved we can add the blended ingredients to the pot.   Simmer this for around 15 - 20 min uncovered to slightly thicken and mellow out the garlic.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":106} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8888/TheHotPickle/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/IMG_1900.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-106\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Take care not to burn yourself and give it a taste.  I found mine needed a little more zip and sweetness so I added a tablespoon of vinegar and a dash of sugar.  Your sauce is done, Perfect!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":107} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8888/TheHotPickle/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/IMG_1901.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-107\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chicken is so good on the BBQ.  It doesn\'t matter if it wings or the whole bird, if it\'s done right it\'s always delicious.  Over the years I\'ve really become fond of using coriander on my chicken breast when I\'m grilling it.  If you haven\'t used it before on chicken you\'ll likely find the flavour reminiscent KFC.  I\'m pretty sure it\'s high on the Colonel\'s list of 11 herbs and spices.  That being said, I only use the whole coriander seeds and muddle them like shown above.  The smell is delicious!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I usually grind up a hand full of whole coriander and whole black pepper then mix them together in a small dish with kosher salt.  I do this so I can grab the spices with my fingers, flip the chicken and rub in spices with my hands and don\'t have to worry about dipping  into the spice bowl afterward since I\'ll use it all anyways.  Cover your chicken generously!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":108} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8888/TheHotPickle/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/IMG_1909.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-108\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now BBQ it!  Get the grill hot enough to get some good grill lines, and throw them on.  I usually flip three times to try for the grill grid pattern and them take a temperature.  If they still need some time after they\'re golden brown just turn down the grill and shut the lid for a few minutes and take the temp again.  Anything over 165f is cooked and if you like your chicken stringier then aim for 180-190f.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":109} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8888/TheHotPickle/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/IMG_1911.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-109\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->', 'BBQ Mango Habanero Chicken', 'It\'s late August and I\'m my pepper plants are finally starting to produce some fruit for the picking.  I\'ve been looking forward to this all summer!  I was feeling like something with a little sweet chilli heat so I decided to pick the first 3 peppers of the year and brew up some mango habanero sauce.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'bbq-mango-habanero-chicken', '', '', '2019-08-28 22:14:32', '2019-08-29 02:14:32', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/TheHotPickle/?p=100', 0, 'post', '', 0),
